# Contributor badges — GitHub sign-in configuration.
#
# The /authors "Your contributor badge" panel identifies the visitor so the
# gentle snark is honestly shown "only to you". Two modes:
#
#   • Real sign-in (the production path): GitHub OAuth **device flow**. Set the
#     client id below and the "Sign in with GitHub" button turns on. No client
#     secret is used (device flow is secret-less), so it is safe to expose.
#
#   • Local dev shim: with nothing set here, a free-text username box lets you
#     preview badges without OAuth. It is DEV-ONLY and never ships to a prod
#     build (see PUBLIC_ALLOW_MANUAL_BADGE to override).
#
# Copy this file to `.env` and fill in the values.

# The Client ID of a GitHub OAuth App with "Device flow" enabled.
# Create one at: https://github.com/settings/developers → New OAuth App →
# tick "Enable Device Flow". Only the Client ID is needed (public value).
PUBLIC_GH_CLIENT_ID=

# Where the browser sends GitHub's device/token calls. GitHub's OAuth endpoints
# send no CORS headers, so they must be proxied.
#   • Local dev: leave as the default "/__gh" — the Vite dev server proxies it
#     to https://github.com (configured in astro.config.mjs).
#   • Production: point this at your own tiny proxy/broker (e.g. a Cloudflare
#     Worker or serverless function) that forwards to https://github.com. This
#     is the one non-static piece a static host (GitHub Pages) can't provide.
PUBLIC_GH_PROXY=/__gh

# Escape hatch: force the dev-only free-text username box on in a production
# build (e.g. a public demo you intentionally want to run without OAuth).
# Leave unset for real deployments so visitors must sign in.
# PUBLIC_ALLOW_MANUAL_BADGE=1
